<h1>Canine &amp; Feline Cardiovascular: Congenital Heart Problems</h1>
<div class="prose max-w-none">
<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="border-collapse:
 collapse;table-layout:fixed">
<col style=""/>
<col span="3" style=""/>
<col style=""/>
<tr height="27" style="height:20.0pt">
<th align="left" class="xl67">Diagnoses</th>
<th align="left" class="xl67">Pathogenesis</th>
<th align="left" class="xl67">Diagnosis</th>
<th align="left" class="xl67">Treatment</th>
<th align="left" class="xl67">Prognosis</th>
</tr>
<tr height="320" style="height:240.0pt">
<td align="left" class="xl66">Patent Ductus Arteriosus (PDA)</td>
<td align="left" class="xl66">Ductus arteriosus;
  normal connection in fetus between pulmonary artery and descending aorta →
  blood bypass lungs directly into systemic circulation. Incr O2 tension and
  decr prostaglandin E2 after birth trigger closure within hours.<br/>
    PDA; Lack of ductal smooth muscle → persistent <span style="font-weight:bold;">left-to-right</span> shunt (aortic pressure &gt; pulmonary artery pressure) → <span style="font-weight:bold;">volume overload</span>.<br/>
    Predis; <span style="color:#805463;">Females</span><span style="font-weight:bold;">. </span>Poodle, Maltese, GSD.<br/>
    Right-to-left shunt if severe as indicates end-stage; fibrosis/hypertension
  → increased resistance/pressure in pulmonary artery exceeds systemic
  pressure.</td>
<td align="left" class="xl66"><span style="text-decoration:underline;">Echocardiogram:</span> <span style="font-weight:bold;">Left atrial/ventricular enlargement</span>, PDA visualization, mitral regurgitation.<br/>
<span style="text-decoration:underline;">Radiographs:</span> Enlarged
  left heart, aneurysmal aorta, pulmonary overcirculation.<br/>
<span style="text-decoration:underline;">PE:</span> <span style="font-weight:bold;">Continuous left basilar</span> murmur
  (washing machine), hyperkinetic <span style="font-weight:bold;">bounding</span> pulses.</td>
<td align="left" class="xl66">Interventional
  catheterization; <span style="font-weight:bold;">coil embolisation</span>/<br/>
    vascular plug. (Most PDAs are <span style="font-weight:bold;">funnel</span> shaped with base at aorta and tip at pulmonary artery).<br/>
    Surgical <span style="font-weight:bold;">ligation</span>; If
  <span style="font-weight:bold;">cylindrical</span> PDA. (Or
  'Nickel-titanium devices Amplatz Canine Ductal Occluder' for cylindrical PDA
  in future)<br/>
    Medical (CHF): Oxygen, diuretics, ACE inhibitors.</td>
<td align="left" class="xl66">Favorable with
  closure.<br/>
<span style="color:#805463;">Poor for right-to-left</span>
  shunt.</td>
</tr>
<tr height="213" style="height:160.0pt">
<td align="left" class="xl65">Vascular Ring Anomaly (Persistent right aortic arch)</td>
<td align="left" class="xl65"><span style="text-decoration:underline;">Normal
  process; Left 4th aortic arch → functional aorta, and the right regresses
  along with the ductus arteriosum (→ ligamentum arteriosum).
    Vascular ring anomaly; Right 4th aortic arch persists → wraps around
  oesophagus +/- trachea (in combo with ligamentum arteriosum on the left) =
  constricting ring → oesophageal dilation cranial to constriction</span> → regurgitation.<br/>
    Predis; GSD, Irish Setter, Great Dane<span style="font-weight:bold;">.</span></td>
<td align="left" class="xl65">Radiographs (+/-
  barium contrast); Megaesophagus, tracheal displacement to left, aspiration
  pneumonia.<br/>
    Angiography; precise confirmation of vascular ring.<br/>
    Endoscopy; Narrowing at the level of heart base, mucosal irritation, food
  buildup in cranial esophagus.</td>
<td align="left" class="xl65">Surgical <span style="color:#805463;">ligation</span> of ligamentum arteriosum
  via left 4th intercostal thoracotomy.<br/>
    Esophageal motility may be impaired → upright feeding, soft or liquid diet,
  multiple small meals</td>
<td align="left" class="xl65">Good if treated <span style="color:#805463;">early</span>; residual esophageal
  dysfunction possible.</td>
</tr>
<tr height="107" style="height:80.0pt">
<td align="left" class="xl66">Ventricular Septal Defect (VSD)</td>
<td align="left" class="xl66">Septal defect → <span style="font-weight:bold;">left-to-right</span> shunting → <span style="font-weight:bold;">left heart</span> volume overload (after
  passing thru lungs).<br/>
    Predis; Springer Spaniel, Bulldog.</td>
<td align="left" class="xl66"><span style="text-decoration:underline;">Echocardiogram:</span> VSD visualization,<span style="color:#805463;"> left heart
  enlargement.</span><br/>
<span style="text-decoration:underline;">Radiographs:</span> Enlarged
  left heart, pulmonary overcirculation.<br/>
<span style="text-decoration:underline;">PE: </span>Loud <span style="color:#805463;">systolic murmur at right sternal border.</span></td>
<td align="left" class="xl66">Surgery; <span style="font-weight:bold;">patch graft</span> or <span style="font-weight:bold;">pulmonary artery banding</span> or
  interventional device closure.<br/>
    Medical; <span style="font-weight:bold;">CHF</span> therapy.</td>
<td align="left" class="xl66">Favorable if small;
  poor for untreated large defects.</td>
</tr>
<tr height="267" style="height:200.0pt">
<td align="left" class="xl65">Tetralogy of Fallot</td>
<td align="left" class="xl65"><span style="font-weight:bold;">1.
  Pulmonic stenosis
    2. Overriding aorta
    3. Ventricular septal defect
    4. Right ventricular hypertrophy
</span>→ <span style="font-weight:bold;">right-to-left </span>shunting → hypoxemia → 2' polycythemia<br/>
    Predis; Keeshond, Bulldog, Mini Poodles, Wire
  Fox Terriers, Scottish Terriers.</td>
<td align="left" class="xl65"><span style="text-decoration:underline;">Echocardiogram:</span> VSD, overriding aorta, RV hypertrophy.<br/>
<span style="text-decoration:underline;">Radiographs:</span> <span style="font-weight:bold;">Right heart enlargement</span>, decreased
  pulmonary vasculature.<br/>
<span style="text-decoration:underline;">PE: </span>Cyanosis, <span style="font-weight:bold;">systolic</span> murmur, <span style="font-weight:bold;">exercise intolerance.</span></td>
<td align="left" class="xl65"><span style="text-decoration:underline;">Medical
  palliative;</span><span style="font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;">
    Phlebotomy</span> for polycythemia (blood removal with
  concurrent fluid replacement).<br/>
<span style="color:#805463;">Hydroxyurea</span>
  (suppresses bone marrow RBC production) if repeated phlebotomies
  unachievable.<br/>
<span style="text-decoration:underline;">Surgery;
</span><span style="color:#805463;">Blalock-Taussig shunt</span><span style="text-decoration:underline;">;
  connects a systemic artery and pulmonary artery to incr bloodflow to lungs.
  For young/unstable patients </span>(Palliative not
  corrective)<br/>
<span style="color:#805463;">Patch graft</span>
  (corrective) to close VSD.</td>
<td align="left" class="xl65">Poor if severe.</td>
</tr>
<tr height="160" style="height:120.0pt">
<td align="left" class="xl66">Atrial Septal Defect (ASD)</td>
<td align="left" class="xl66">Defect in atrial
  septum → <span style="font-weight:bold;">left-to-right</span>
  shunting → <span style="font-weight:bold;">right heart</span>
  volume overload.<br/>
    Predis; Boxer, Poodle.</td>
<td align="left" class="xl66"><span style="text-decoration:underline;">Echocardiogram:</span> Right heart enlargement, ASD
  visualisation.<br/>
<span style="text-decoration:underline;">Radiographs:</span> Enlarged
  right heart, pulmonary overcirculation.<br/>
<span style="text-decoration:underline;">PE: </span>Grade <span style="color:#805463;">2-3/6 Systolic left basilar </span>murmur,
  split second heart sound.</td>
<td align="left" class="xl66">Surgery; <span style="color:#805463;">patch graft </span>or interventional device
  closure.<br/>
    Medical; CHF therapy.</td>
<td align="left" class="xl66">Favorable if small;
  poor for untreated large defects.</td>
</tr>
<tr height="187" style="height:140.0pt">
<td align="left" class="xl65">Atrioventricular Valvular Dysplasia</td>
<td align="left" class="xl65">Valve malformation → <span style="font-weight:bold;">regurgitation</span> (backflow) <span style="font-weight:bold;">or stenosis </span>(narrowing of valve
  orifice, restricting blood flow)<span style="font-weight:bold;">
</span>Leaflets: thickened, shortened, or
  displaced<br/>
    Chordae tendineae: abnormal length or absence<br/>
    Papillary muscles: abnormal insertion or development<br/>
    Predis; Labs, GSD, Great Dane, large breed
  males predisposed to <span style="font-weight:bold;">Tricupsid</span> dysplasia.</td>
<td align="left" class="xl65"><span style="text-decoration:underline;">Echocardiogram:</span> Valve thickening, leaflet
  displacement, chamber dilation, and regurgitant jets<br/>
<span style="text-decoration:underline;">Radiographs: </span>Heart
  chamber enlargement, signs of CHF.<br/>
<span style="text-decoration:underline;">PE: </span>Systolic murmur <span style="color:#805463;">(right side tricuspid, left side mitral</span>).<br/>
    Advanced <span style="color:#805463;">tricuspid</span>
  dysplasia may show right-side heart failure signs (<span style="color:#805463;">ascites
  and hepatomegaly</span>).</td>
<td align="left" class="xl65">Surgery; <span style="color:#805463;">valve repair</span>/replacement.<br/>
    Medical; <span style="color:#805463;">CHF</span> therapy,
  <span style="color:#805463;">antiarrhythmics</span>.</td>
<td align="left" class="xl65">Variable based on
  severity.</td>
</tr>
<tr height="160" style="height:120.0pt">
<td align="left" class="xl66">Peritoneopericardial diaphragmatic hernia (PPDH)</td>
<td align="left" class="xl66">Failure of <span style="color:#805463;">septum transversum fusion</span> → Abnormal
  communication between peritoneal and pericardial cavities → abdominal organs <span style="color:#805463;">herniate into pericardial sac</span>.<br/>
    The most common congenital pericardial disease in small animals.<br/>
    Predis; Weimaraners, Persian &amp; Himalayan
  cats.</td>
<td align="left" class="xl66"><span style="text-decoration:underline;">Radiographs:</span> Cardiomegaly, <span style="color:#805463;">silhouette</span> between heart &amp; diaphragm.<br/>
<span style="text-decoration:underline;">PE:</span> Can be <span style="color:#805463;">asymptomatic</span>. Respiratory distress, exercise intolerance, GIT signs if
  bowel involved, muffled heart sounds (pericardial space compression).</td>
<td align="left" class="xl66">Surgery: <span style="color:#805463;">Hernia repair</span> (herniorrhaphy) via

  midline laparotomy in symptomatic cases.</td>
<td align="left" class="xl66"><span style="font-weight:bold;">Excellent</span> unless <span style="font-weight:bold;">adhesions</span> between abdominal organs and pericardium complicate surgery.</td>
</tr>
